    "body": "Here's the short version:\nUnless you plan on people using this code in 100+ years (literally), _and_\nyou want to sue someone _in 100_ years over it, don't worry about updating\nthe copyright years.\n\nOn Wed, Feb 3, 2016 at 3:39 PM, David Symonds notifications@github.com\nwrote:\n\n> The general guidance I've always received from lawyers (and from places\n> like http://www.copyright.gov/eco/help-publication.html) is that if\n> you're updating a source file, don't increase the year of copyright\n> notices, since the copyright applies to when the source file was first\n> committed, and doesn't refresh/extend just because some minor change is\n> made to it (which would permit indefinite copyright extension!).\n> \n> check_copyright.py is demanding that copyright years cover the current\n> year (e.g. #5041 https://github.com/grpc/grpc/pull/5041). It's fine for\n> the year of the notice to be extended (e.g. 2015 -> 2015-2016), but it's\n> unnecessary, and leads people to change instead of extend it (e.g. 2015\n> -> 2016), which is wrong.\n> \n> @ejona86 https://github.com/ejona86 @dberlin\n> https://github.com/dberlin @ctiller https://github.com/ctiller\n> \n> â€”\n> Reply to this email directly or view it on GitHub\n> https://github.com/grpc/grpc/issues/5051.\n"
